Analysis with a subset of the data


Data Cleaning

Besides the data cleaning already applied to the full dataset and explained in the Colorado_Fulldataset document, in this stage we removed tweets sent by Twitter accounts from official agencies since we aim to analyze what general public post. In this stage 6% of the tweets were excluded. 228 tweets from the 4086 total tweets.

Now I will repeat the same analysis but considering tweets sent from what should be the affected area (by using spatial clustering) and within the Flood phase of the disaster.

Before doing so, the data was first projected in North America Lambert Conformal Conic.

## Coordinate Reference System:
##   No EPSG code
##   proj4string: "+proj=lcc +lat_1=20 +lat_2=60 +lat_0=40 +lon_0=-96 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0,0,0,0,0 +units=m +no_defs"


Subsetting by Spatial Clustering

In order to identify tweets sent from the afected area, a hierarchical implementation of dbscan was used (hdscan). For spatial hierarchical clustering we need to pick a number of minimum points to be considered to identify the cluster. When setting that number with any value betweet 315 and 340, clusters in Colorado were identify. So we picked the minimum value in that range: 315.

Most common words (Within Spatial Clusters)

After the spatial filter and filtering only tweets sent during the Flood stage only 16% of the total tweets were retained. 652 tweets from the 4086 total.

A quick view of the most common words in the whole dataset:

Again, since boulder is the most common word and is going to have a big effect in our topic modelling, it was removed from the dataset. The following four terms (boulderflood, colorado, cowx, flood) were also excluded because they were so common and used neutrally in all four stages. After excluding these six terms, the new list of common words looks as follows:
